41Mk 4:13 Then Jesus asked them, "Don't you understand this parable? How, then, will you ever understand any parable? 
41Mk 4:14 The sower sows God's message. 
41Mk 4:15 Some people are like the seeds that fall along the path; as soon as they hear the message, Satan comes and takes it away. 
41Mk 4:16 Other people are like the seeds that fall on rocky ground. As soon as they hear the message, they receive it gladly. 
41Mk 4:17 But it does not sink deep into them, and they don't last long. So when trouble or persecution comes because of the message, they give up at once. 
41Mk 4:18 Other people are like the seeds sown among the thorn bushes. These are the ones who hear the message, 
41Mk 4:19 but the worries about this life, the love for riches, and all other kinds of desires crowd in and choke the message, and they don't bear fruit. 
41Mk 4:20 But other people are like seeds sown in good soil. They hear the message, accept it, and bear fruit�� some thirty, some sixty, and some one hundred." 
41Mk 4:21 Jesus continued, "Does anyone ever bring in a lamp and put it under a bowl or under the bed? Isn't it put on the lampstand? 
41Mk 4:22 Whatever is hidden away will be brought out into the open, and whatever is covered up will be uncovered. 
41Mk 4:23 Listen, then, if you have ears!" 
41Mk 4:24 He also said to them, "Pay attention to what you hear! The same rules you use to judge others will be used by God to judge you - -but with even greater severity. 
41Mk 4:25 Those who have something will be given more, and those who have nothing will have taken away from them even the little they have." 
41Mk 4:26 Jesus went on to say, "The Kingdom of God is like this. A man scatters seed in his field. 
41Mk 4:27 He sleeps at night, is up and about during the day, and all the while the seeds are sprouting and growing. Yet he does not know how it happens. 
41Mk 4:28 The soil itself makes the plants grow and bear fruit; first the tender stalk appears, then the head, and finally the head full of grain. 
41Mk 4:29 When the grain is ripe, the man starts cutting it with his sickle, because harvest time has come. 
41Mk 4:30 "What shall we say the Kingdom of God is like?" asked Jesus. "What parable shall we use to explain it? 
41Mk 4:31 It is like this. A man takes a mustard seed, the smallest seed in the world, and plants it in the ground. 
41Mk 4:32 After a while it grows up and becomes the biggest of all plants. It puts out such large branches that the birds come and make their nests in its shade." 
41Mk 4:33 Jesus preached his message to the people, using many other parables like these; he told them as much as they could understand. 
41Mk 4:34 He would not speak to them without using parables, but when he was alone with his disciples, he would explain everything to them. 
41Mk 4:35 On the evening of that same day Jesus said to his disciples, "Let us go across to the other side of the lake." 
