41Mk 13:14 "You will see 'The Awful Horror' standing in the place where he should not be." (Note to the reader�� understand what this means!) "Then those who are in Judea must run away to the hills. 
41Mk 13:15 Someone who is on the roof of a house must not lose time by going down into the house to get anything to take along. 
41Mk 13:16 Someone who is in the field must not go back to the house for a cloak. 
41Mk 13:17 How terrible it will be in those days for women who are pregnant and for mothers with little babies! 
41Mk 13:18 Pray to God that these things will not happen in the winter! 
41Mk 13:19 For the trouble of those days will be far worse than any the world has ever known from the very beginning when God created the world until the present time. Nor will there ever be anything like it again. 
41Mk 13:20 But the Lord has reduced the number of those days; if he had not, nobody would survive. For the sake of his chosen people, however, he has reduced those days. 
41Mk 13:21 "Then, if anyone says to you, 'Look, here is the Messiah!' or, 'Look, there he is!' - -do not believe it. 
41Mk 13:22 For false Messiahs and false prophets will appear. They will perform miracles and wonders in order to deceive even God's chosen people, if possible. 
41Mk 13:23 Be on your guard! I have told you everything ahead of time. 
41Mk 13:24 "In the days after that time of trouble the sun will grow dark, the moon will no longer shine, 
41Mk 13:25 the stars will fall from heaven, and the powers in space will be driven from their courses. 
41Mk 13:26 Then the Son of Man will appear, coming in the clouds with great power and glory. 
41Mk 13:27 He will send the angels out to the four corners of the earth to gather God's chosen people from one end of the world to the other. 
41Mk 13:28 "Let the fig tree teach you a lesson. When its branches become green and tender and it starts putting out leaves, you know that summer is near. 
41Mk 13:29 In the same way, when you see these things happening, you will know that the time is near, ready to begin. 
41Mk 13:30 Remember that all these things will happen before the people now living have all died. 
41Mk 13:31 Heaven and earth will pass away, but my words will never pass away. 
41Mk 13:32 "No one knows, however, when that day or hour will come - -neither the angels in heaven, nor the Son; only the Father knows. 
41Mk 13:33 Be on watch, be alert, for you do not know when the time will come. 
41Mk 13:34 It will be like a man who goes away from home on a trip and leaves his servants in charge, after giving to each one his own work to do and after telling the doorkeeper to keep watch. 
41Mk 13:35 Watch, then, because you do not know when the master of the house is coming - -it might be in the evening or at midnight or before dawn or at sunrise. 
41Mk 13:36 If he comes suddenly, he must not find you asleep. 
41Mk 13:37 What I say to you, then, I say to all�� Watch!" 
41Mk 14:1 It was now two days before the Festival of Passover and Unleavened Bread. The chief priests and the teachers of the Law were looking for a way to arrest Jesus secretly and put him to death. 
41Mk 14:2 "We must not do it during the festival," they said, "or the people might riot." 
41Mk 14:3 Jesus was in Bethany at the house of Simon, a man who had suffered from a dreaded skin disease. While Jesus was eating, a woman came in with an alabaster jar full of a very expensive perfume made of pure nard. She broke the jar and poured the perfume on Jesus' head. 
41Mk 14:4 Some of the people there became angry and said to one another, "What was the use of wasting the perfume? 
41Mk 14:5 It could have been sold for more than three hundred silver coins and the money given to the poor!" And they criticized her harshly. 
41Mk 14:6 But Jesus said, "Leave her alone! Why are you bothering her? She has done a fine and beautiful thing for me. 
41Mk 14:7 You will always have poor people with you, and any time you want to, you can help them. But you will not always have me. 
41Mk 14:8 She did what she could; she poured perfume on my body to prepare it ahead of time for burial. 
41Mk 14:9 Now, I assure you that wherever the gospel is preached all over the world, what she has done will be told in memory of her." 
41Mk 14:10 Then Judas Iscariot, one of the twelve disciples, went off to the chief priests in order to betray Jesus to them. 
41Mk 14:11 They were pleased to hear what he had to say, and promised to give him money. So Judas started looking for a good chance to hand Jesus over to them. 
41Mk 14:12 On the first day of the Festival of Unleavened Bread, the day the lambs for the Passover meal were killed, Jesus' disciples asked him, "Where do you want us to go and get the Passover meal ready for you?" 
41Mk 14:13 Then Jesus sent two of them with these instructions�� "Go into the city, and a man carrying a jar of water will meet you. Follow him 
41Mk 14:14 to the house he enters, and say to the owner of the house�� 'The Teacher says, Where is the room where my disciples and I will eat the Passover meal?' 
41Mk 14:15 Then he will show you a large upstairs room, fixed up and furnished, where you will get everything ready for us." 
41Mk 14:16 The disciples left, went to the city, and found everything just as Jesus had told them; and they prepared the Passover meal. 
41Mk 14:17 When it was evening, Jesus came with the twelve disciples. 
41Mk 14:18 While they were at the table eating, Jesus said, "I tell you that one of you will betray me - -one who is eating with me." 
41Mk 14:19 The disciples were upset and began to ask him, one after the other, "Surely you don't mean me, do you?" 
41Mk 14:20 Jesus answered, "It will be one of you twelve, one who dips his bread in the dish with me. 
41Mk 14:21 The Son of Man will die as the Scriptures say he will; but how terrible for that man who will betray the Son of Man! It would have been better for that man if he had never been born!" 
41Mk 14:22 While they were eating, Jesus took a piece of bread, gave a prayer of thanks, broke it, and gave it to his disciples. "Take it," he said, "this is my body." 
41Mk 14:23 Then he took a cup, gave thanks to God, and handed it to them; and they all drank from it. 
41Mk 14:24 Jesus said, "This is my blood which is poured out for many, my blood which seals God's covenant. 
41Mk 14:25 I tell you, I will never again drink this wine until the day I drink the new wine in the Kingdom of God." 
41Mk 14:26 Then they sang a hymn and went out to the Mount of Olives. 
41Mk 14:27 Jesus said to them, "All of you will run away and leave me, for the scripture says, 'God will kill the shepherd, and the sheep will all be scattered.' 
41Mk 14:28 But after I am raised to life, I will go to Galilee ahead of you." 
41Mk 14:29 Peter answered, "I will never leave you, even though all the rest do!" 
41Mk 14:30 Jesus said to Peter, "I tell you that before the rooster crows two times tonight, you will say three times that you do not know me." 
41Mk 14:31 Peter answered even more strongly, "I will never say that, even if I have to die with you!" And all the other disciples said the same thing. 
41Mk 14:32 They came to a place called Gethsemane, and Jesus said to his disciples, "Sit here while I pray." 
41Mk 14:33 He took Peter, James, and John with him. Distress and anguish came over him, 
41Mk 14:34 and he said to them, "The sorrow in my heart is so great that it almost crushes me. Stay here and keep watch." 
41Mk 14:35 He went a little farther on, threw himself on the ground, and prayed that, if possible, he might not have to go through that time of suffering. 
41Mk 14:36 "Father," he prayed, "my Father! All things are possible for you. Take this cup of suffering away from me. Yet not what I want, but what you want." 
41Mk 14:37 Then he returned and found the three disciples asleep. He said to Peter, "Simon, are you asleep? Weren't you able to stay awake for even one hour?" 
41Mk 14:38 And he said to them, "Keep watch, and pray that you will not fall into temptation. The spirit is willing, but the flesh is weak." 
41Mk 14:39 He went away once more and prayed, saying the same words. 
41Mk 14:40 Then he came back to the disciples and found them asleep; they could not keep their eyes open. And they did not know what to say to him. 
41Mk 14:41 When he came back the third time, he said to them, "Are you still sleeping and resting? Enough! The hour has come! Look, the Son of Man is now being handed over to the power of sinners. 
41Mk 14:42 Get up, let us go. Look, here is the man who is betraying me!" 
41Mk 14:43 Jesus was still speaking when Judas, one of the twelve disciples, arrived. With him was a crowd armed with swords and clubs and sent by the chief priests, the teachers of the Law, and the elders. 
41Mk 14:44 The traitor had given the crowd a signal�� "The man I kiss is the one you want. Arrest him and take him away under guard." 
41Mk 14:45 As soon as Judas arrived, he went up to Jesus and said, "Teacher!" and kissed him. 
41Mk 14:46 So they arrested Jesus and held him tight. 
41Mk 14:47 But one of those standing there drew his sword and struck at the High Priest's slave, cutting off his ear. 
41Mk 14:48 Then Jesus spoke up and said to them, "Did you have to come with swords and clubs to capture me, as though I were an outlaw? 
41Mk 14:49 Day after day I was with you teaching in the Temple, and you did not arrest me. But the Scriptures must come true." 
41Mk 14:50 Then all the disciples left him and ran away. 
41Mk 14:51 A certain young man, dressed only in a linen cloth, was following Jesus. They tried to arrest him, 
41Mk 14:52 but he ran away naked, leaving the cloth behind. 
41Mk 14:53 Then Jesus was taken to the High Priest's house, where all the chief priests, the elders, and the teachers of the Law were gathering. 
41Mk 14:54 Peter followed from a distance and went into the courtyard of the High Priest's house. There he sat down with the guards, keeping himself warm by the fire. 
41Mk 14:55 The chief priests and the whole Council tried to find some evidence against Jesus in order to put him to death, but they could not find any. 
41Mk 14:56 Many witnesses told lies against Jesus, but their stories did not agree. 
41Mk 14:57 Then some men stood up and told this lie against Jesus�� 
41Mk 14:58 "We heard him say, 'I will tear down this Temple which men have made, and after three days I will build one that is not made by men.' " 
41Mk 14:59 Not even they, however, could make their stories agree. 
41Mk 14:60 The High Priest stood up in front of them all and questioned Jesus, "Have you no answer to the accusation they bring against you?" 
41Mk 14:61 But Jesus kept quiet and would not say a word. Again the High Priest questioned him, "Are you the Messiah, the Son of the Blessed God?" 
41Mk 14:62 "I am," answered Jesus, "and you will all see the Son of Man seated at the right side of the Almighty and coming with the clouds of heaven!" 
41Mk 14:63 The High Priest tore his robes and said, "We don't need any more witnesses! 
41Mk 14:64 You heard his blasphemy. What is your decision?" They all voted against him�� he was guilty and should be put to death. 
41Mk 14:65 Some of them began to spit on Jesus, and they blindfolded him and hit him. "Guess who hit you!" they said. And the guards took him and slapped him. 
41Mk 14:66 Peter was still down in the courtyard when one of the High Priest's servant women came by. 
41Mk 14:67 When she saw Peter warming himself, she looked straight at him and said, "You, too, were with Jesus of Nazareth." 
41Mk 14:68 But he denied it. "I don't know...I don't understand what you are talking about," he answered, and went out into the passageway. Just then a rooster crowed. 
41Mk 14:69 The servant woman saw him there and began to repeat to the bystanders, "He is one of them!" 
41Mk 14:70 But Peter denied it again. A little while later the bystanders accused Peter again, "You can't deny that you are one of them, because you, too, are from Galilee." 
41Mk 14:71 Then Peter said, "I swear that I am telling the truth! May God punish me if I am not! I do not know the man you are talking about!" 
41Mk 14:72 Just then a rooster crowed a second time, and Peter remembered how Jesus had said to him, "Before the rooster crows two times, you will say three times that you do not know me." And he broke down and cried. 
41Mk 15:1 Early in the morning the chief priests met hurriedly with the elders, the teachers of the Law, and the whole Council, and made their plans. They put Jesus in chains, led him away, and handed him over to Pilate. 
41Mk 15:2 Pilate questioned him, "Are you the king of the Jews?" Jesus answered, "So you say." 
41Mk 15:3 The chief priests were accusing Jesus of many things, 
41Mk 15:4 so Pilate questioned him again, "Aren't you going to answer? Listen to all their accusations!" 
41Mk 15:5 Again Jesus refused to say a word, and Pilate was amazed. 
41Mk 15:6 At every Passover Festival Pilate was in the habit of setting free any one prisoner the people asked for. 
41Mk 15:7 At that time a man named Barabbas was in prison with the rebels who had committed murder in the riot. 
41Mk 15:8 When the crowd gathered and began to ask Pilate for the usual favor, 
41Mk 15:9 he asked them, "Do you want me to set free for you the king of the Jews?" 
41Mk 15:10 He knew very well that the chief priests had handed Jesus over to him because they were jealous. 
41Mk 15:11 But the chief priests stirred up the crowd to ask, instead, that Pilate set Barabbas free for them. 
41Mk 15:12 Pilate spoke again to the crowd, "What, then, do you want me to do with the one you call the king of the Jews?" 
41Mk 15:13 They shouted back, "Crucify him!" 
41Mk 15:14 "But what crime has he committed?" Pilate asked. They shouted all the louder, "Crucify him!" 
41Mk 15:15 Pilate wanted to please the crowd, so he set Barabbas free for them. Then he had Jesus whipped and handed him over to be crucified. 
41Mk 15:16 The soldiers took Jesus inside to the courtyard of the governor's palace and called together the rest of the company. 
41Mk 15:17 They put a purple robe on Jesus, made a crown out of thorny branches, and put it on his head. 
41Mk 15:18 Then they began to salute him�� "Long live the King of the Jews!" 
41Mk 15:19 They beat him over the head with a stick, spat on him, fell on their knees, and bowed down to him. 
41Mk 15:20 When they had finished making fun of him, they took off the purple robe and put his own clothes back on him. Then they led him out to crucify him. 
41Mk 15:21 On the way they met a man named Simon, who was coming into the city from the country, and the soldiers forced him to carry Jesus' cross. (Simon was from Cyrene and was the father of Alexander and Rufus.) 
41Mk 15:22 They took Jesus to a place called Golgotha, which means "The Place of the Skull." 
41Mk 15:23 There they tried to give him wine mixed with a drug called myrrh, but Jesus would not drink it. 
41Mk 15:24 Then they crucified him and divided his clothes among themselves, throwing dice to see who would get which piece of clothing. 
41Mk 15:25 It was nine o'clock in the morning when they crucified him. 
41Mk 15:26 The notice of the accusation against him said�� "The King of the Jews." 
41Mk 15:27 They also crucified two bandits with Jesus, one on his right and the other on his left. 
