42Lk 22:4 So Judas went off and spoke with the chief priests and the officers of the Temple guard about how he could betray Jesus to them. 
42Lk 22:5 They were pleased and offered to pay him money. 
42Lk 22:6 Judas agreed to it and started looking for a good chance to hand Jesus over to them without the people knowing about it. 
42Lk 22:7 The day came during the Festival of Unleavened Bread when the lambs for the Passover meal were to be killed. 
42Lk 22:8 Jesus sent Peter and John with these instructions�� "Go and get the Passover meal ready for us to eat." 
42Lk 22:9 "Where do you want us to get it ready?" they asked him. 
42Lk 22:10 He answered, "As you go into the city, a man carrying a jar of water will meet you. Follow him into the house that he enters, 
42Lk 22:11 and say to the owner of the house�� 'The Teacher says to you, Where is the room where my disciples and I will eat the Passover meal?' 
42Lk 22:12 He will show you a large furnished room upstairs, where you will get everything ready." 
42Lk 22:13 They went off and found everything just as Jesus had told them, and they prepared the Passover meal. 
42Lk 22:14 When the hour came, Jesus took his place at the table with the apostles. 
42Lk 22:15 He said to them, "I have wanted so much to eat this Passover meal with you before I suffer! 
42Lk 22:16 For I tell you, I will never eat it until it is given its full meaning in the Kingdom of God." 
42Lk 22:17 Then Jesus took a cup, gave thanks to God, and said, "Take this and share it among yourselves. 
42Lk 22:18 I tell you that from now on I will not drink this wine until the Kingdom of God comes." 
42Lk 22:19 Then he took a piece of bread, gave thanks to God, broke it, and gave it to them, saying, "This is my body, which is given for you. Do this in memory of me." 
42Lk 22:20 In the same way, he gave them the cup after the supper, saying, "This cup is God's new covenant sealed with my blood, which is poured out for you. 
42Lk 22:21 "But, look! The one who betrays me is here at the table with me! 
42Lk 22:22 The Son of Man will die as God has decided, but how terrible for that man who betrays him!" 
42Lk 22:23 Then they began to ask among themselves which one of them it could be who was going to do this. 
42Lk 22:24 An argument broke out among the disciples as to which one of them should be thought of as the greatest. 
42Lk 22:25 Jesus said to them, "The kings of the pagans have power over their people, and the rulers claim the title 'Friends of the People.' 
42Lk 22:26 But this is not the way it is with you; rather, the greatest one among you must be like the youngest, and the leader must be like the servant. 
42Lk 22:27 Who is greater, the one who sits down to eat or the one who serves? The one who sits down, of course. But I am among you as one who serves. 
42Lk 22:28 "You have stayed with me all through my trials; 
42Lk 22:29 and just as my Father has given me the right to rule, so I will give you the same right. 
42Lk 22:30 You will eat and drink at my table in my Kingdom, and you will sit on thrones to rule over the twelve tribes of Israel. 
42Lk 22:31 "Simon, Simon! Listen! Satan has received permission to test all of you, to separate the good from the bad, as a farmer separates the wheat from the chaff. 
42Lk 22:32 But I have prayed for you, Simon, that your faith will not fail. And when you turn back to me, you must strengthen your brothers." 
42Lk 22:33 Peter answered, "Lord, I am ready to go to prison with you and to die with you!" 
42Lk 22:34 "I tell you, Peter," Jesus said, "the rooster will not crow tonight until you have said three times that you do not know me." 
42Lk 22:35 Then Jesus asked his disciples, "When I sent you out that time without purse, bag, or shoes, did you lack anything?" "Not a thing," they answered. 
42Lk 22:36 "But now," Jesus said, "whoever has a purse or a bag must take it; and whoever does not have a sword must sell his coat and buy one. 
42Lk 22:37 For I tell you that the scripture which says, 'He shared the fate of criminals,' must come true about me, because what was written about me is coming true." 
42Lk 22:38 The disciples said, "Look! Here are two swords, Lord!" "That is enough!" he replied. 
42Lk 22:39 Jesus left the city and went, as he usually did, to the Mount of Olives; and the disciples went with him. 
42Lk 22:40 When he arrived at the place, he said to them, "Pray that you will not fall into temptation." 
42Lk 22:41 Then he went off from them about the distance of a stone's throw and knelt down and prayed. 
42Lk 22:42 "Father," he said, "if you will, take this cup of suffering away from me. Not my will, however, but your will be done." 
42Lk 22:43 An angel from heaven appeared to him and strengthened him. 
42Lk 22:44 In great anguish he prayed even more fervently; his sweat was like drops of blood falling to the ground. 
42Lk 22:45 Rising from his prayer, he went back to the disciples and found them asleep, worn out by their grief. 
42Lk 22:46 He said to them, "Why are you sleeping? Get up and pray that you will not fall into temptation." 
42Lk 22:47 Jesus was still speaking when a crowd arrived, led by Judas, one of the twelve disciples. He came up to Jesus to kiss him. 
42Lk 22:48 But Jesus said, "Judas, is it with a kiss that you betray the Son of Man?" 
42Lk 22:49 When the disciples who were with Jesus saw what was going to happen, they asked, "Shall we use our swords, Lord?" 
42Lk 22:50 And one of them struck the High Priest's slave and cut off his right ear. 
42Lk 22:51 But Jesus said, "Enough of this!" He touched the man's ear and healed him. 
42Lk 22:52 Then Jesus said to the chief priests and the officers of the Temple guard and the elders who had come there to get him, "Did you have to come with swords and clubs, as though I were an outlaw? 
42Lk 22:53 I was with you in the Temple every day, and you did not try to arrest me. But this is your hour to act, when the power of darkness rules." 
42Lk 22:54 They arrested Jesus and took him away into the house of the High Priest; and Peter followed at a distance. 
42Lk 22:55 A fire had been lit in the center of the courtyard, and Peter joined those who were sitting around it. 
42Lk 22:56 When one of the servant women saw him sitting there at the fire, she looked straight at him and said, "This man too was with Jesus!" 
42Lk 22:57 But Peter denied it, "Woman, I don't even know him!" 
42Lk 22:58 After a little while a man noticed Peter and said, "You are one of them, too!" But Peter answered, "Man, I am not!" 
42Lk 22:59 And about an hour later another man insisted strongly, "There isn't any doubt that this man was with Jesus, because he also is a Galilean!" 
42Lk 22:60 But Peter answered, "Man, I don't know what you are talking about!" At once, while he was still speaking, a rooster crowed. 
42Lk 22:61 The Lord turned around and looked straight at Peter, and Peter remembered that the Lord had said to him, "Before the rooster crows tonight, you will say three times that you do not know me." 
42Lk 22:62 Peter went out and wept bitterly. 
42Lk 22:63 The men who were guarding Jesus made fun of him and beat him. 
42Lk 22:64 They blindfolded him and asked him, "Who hit you? Guess!" 
42Lk 22:65 And they said many other insulting things to him. 
42Lk 22:66 When day came, the elders, the chief priests, and the teachers of the Law met together, and Jesus was brought before the Council. 
42Lk 22:67 "Tell us," they said, "are you the Messiah?" He answered, "If I tell you, you will not believe me; 
42Lk 22:68 and if I ask you a question, you will not answer. 
42Lk 22:69 But from now on the Son of Man will be seated at the right side of Almighty God." 
42Lk 22:70 They all said, "Are you, then, the Son of God?" He answered them, "You say that I am." 
42Lk 22:71 And they said, "We don't need any witnesses! We ourselves have heard what he said!" 
42Lk 23:1 The whole group rose up and took Jesus before Pilate, 
42Lk 23:2 where they began to accuse him�� "We caught this man misleading our people, telling them not to pay taxes to the Emperor and claiming that he himself is the Messiah, a king." 
42Lk 23:3 Pilate asked him, "Are you the king of the Jews?" "So you say," answered Jesus. 
42Lk 23:4 Then Pilate said to the chief priests and the crowds, "I find no reason to condemn this man." 
42Lk 23:5 But they insisted even more strongly, "With his teaching he is starting a riot among the people all through Judea. He began in Galilee and now has come here." 
42Lk 23:6 When Pilate heard this, he asked, "Is this man a Galilean?" 
42Lk 23:7 When he learned that Jesus was from the region ruled by Herod, he sent him to Herod, who was also in Jerusalem at that time. 
42Lk 23:8 Herod was very pleased when he saw Jesus, because he had heard about him and had been wanting to see him for a long time. He was hoping to see Jesus perform some miracle. 
42Lk 23:9 So Herod asked Jesus many questions, but Jesus made no answer. 
42Lk 23:10 The chief priests and the teachers of the Law stepped forward and made strong accusations against Jesus. 
42Lk 23:11 Herod and his soldiers made fun of Jesus and treated him with contempt; then they put a fine robe on him and sent him back to Pilate. 
42Lk 23:12 On that very day Herod and Pilate became friends; before this they had been enemies. 
42Lk 23:13 Pilate called together the chief priests, the leaders, and the people, 
42Lk 23:14 and said to them, "You brought this man to me and said that he was misleading the people. Now, I have examined him here in your presence, and I have not found him guilty of any of the crimes you accuse him of. 
42Lk 23:15 Nor did Herod find him guilty, for he sent him back to us. There is nothing this man has done to deserve death. 
42Lk 23:16 So I will have him whipped and let him go." 
42Lk 23:17 OMITTED TEXT
42Lk 23:18 The whole crowd cried out, "Kill him! Set Barabbas free for us!" 
42Lk 23:19 (Barabbas had been put in prison for a riot that had taken place in the city, and for murder.) 
42Lk 23:20 Pilate wanted to set Jesus free, so he appealed to the crowd again. 
42Lk 23:21 But they shouted back, "Crucify him! Crucify him!" 
42Lk 23:22 Pilate said to them the third time, "But what crime has he committed? I cannot find anything he has done to deserve death! I will have him whipped and set him free." 
42Lk 23:23 But they kept on shouting at the top of their voices that Jesus should be crucified, and finally their shouting succeeded. 
42Lk 23:24 So Pilate passed the sentence on Jesus that they were asking for. 
42Lk 23:25 He set free the man they wanted, the one who had been put in prison for riot and murder, and he handed Jesus over for them to do as they wished. 
42Lk 23:26 The soldiers led Jesus away, and as they were going, they met a man from Cyrene named Simon who was coming into the city from the country. They seized him, put the cross on him, and made him carry it behind Jesus. 
42Lk 23:27 A large crowd of people followed him; among them were some women who were weeping and wailing for him. 
42Lk 23:28 Jesus turned to them and said, "Women of Jerusalem! Don't cry for me, but for yourselves and your children. 
42Lk 23:29 For the days are coming when people will say, 'How lucky are the women who never had children, who never bore babies, who never nursed them!' 
42Lk 23:30 That will be the time when people will say to the mountains, 'Fall on us!' and to the hills, 'Hide us!' 
42Lk 23:31 For if such things as these are done when the wood is green, what will happen when it is dry?" 
42Lk 23:32 Two other men, both of them criminals, were also led out to be put to death with Jesus. 
42Lk 23:33 When they came to the place called "The Skull," they crucified Jesus there, and the two criminals, one on his right and the other on his left. 
42Lk 23:34 Jesus said, "Forgive them, Father! They don't know what they are doing." They divided his clothes among themselves by throwing dice. 
42Lk 23:35 The people stood there watching while the Jewish leaders made fun of him�� "He saved others; let him save himself if he is the Messiah whom God has chosen!" 
42Lk 23:36 The soldiers also made fun of him�� they came up to him and offered him cheap wine, 
42Lk 23:37 and said, "Save yourself if you are the king of the Jews!" 
42Lk 23:38 Above him were written these words�� "This is the King of the Jews." 
42Lk 23:39 One of the criminals hanging there hurled insults at him�� "Aren't you the Messiah? Save yourself and us!" 
42Lk 23:40 The other one, however, rebuked him, saying, "Don't you fear God? You received the same sentence he did. 
42Lk 23:41 Ours, however, is only right, because we are getting what we deserve for what we did; but he has done no wrong." 
42Lk 23:42 And he said to Jesus, "Remember me, Jesus, when you come as King!" 
42Lk 23:43 Jesus said to him, "I promise you that today you will be in Paradise with me." 
42Lk 23:44 It was about twelve o'clock when the sun stopped shining and darkness covered the whole country until three o'clock; 
42Lk 23:45 and the curtain hanging in the Temple was torn in two. 
42Lk 23:46 Jesus cried out in a loud voice, "Father! In your hands I place my spirit!" He said this and died. 
42Lk 23:47 The army officer saw what had happened, and he praised God, saying, "Certainly he was a good man!" 
42Lk 23:48 When the people who had gathered there to watch the spectacle saw what happened, they all went back home, beating their breasts in sorrow. 
42Lk 23:49 All those who knew Jesus personally, including the women who had followed him from Galilee, stood at a distance to watch. 
42Lk 23:50 There was a man named Joseph from Arimathea, a town in Judea. He was a good and honorable man, who was waiting for the coming of the Kingdom of God. 
42Lk 23:51 Although he was a member of the Council, he had not agreed with their decision and action. 
42Lk 23:52 He went into the presence of Pilate and asked for the body of Jesus. 
42Lk 23:53 Then he took the body down, wrapped it in a linen sheet, and placed it in a tomb which had been dug out of solid rock and which had never been used. 
42Lk 23:54 It was Friday, and the Sabbath was about to begin. 
42Lk 23:55 The women who had followed Jesus from Galilee went with Joseph and saw the tomb and how Jesus' body was placed in it. 
42Lk 23:56 Then they went back home and prepared the spices and perfumes for the body. On the Sabbath they rested, as the Law commanded. 
42Lk 24:1 Very early on Sunday morning the women went to the tomb, carrying the spices they had prepared. 
42Lk 24:2 They found the stone rolled away from the entrance to the tomb, 
42Lk 24:3 so they went in; but they did not find the body of the Lord Jesus. 
42Lk 24:4 They stood there puzzled about this, when suddenly two men in bright shining clothes stood by them. 
42Lk 24:5 Full of fear, the women bowed down to the ground, as the men said to them, "Why are you looking among the dead for one who is alive? 
42Lk 24:6 He is not here; he has been raised. Remember what he said to you while he was in Galilee�� 
42Lk 24:7 'The Son of Man must be handed over to sinners, be crucified, and three days later rise to life.' " 
42Lk 24:8 Then the women remembered his words, 
42Lk 24:9 returned from the tomb, and told all these things to the eleven disciples and all the rest. 
42Lk 24:10 The women were Mary Magdalene, Joanna, and Mary the mother of James; they and the other women with them told these things to the apostles. 
42Lk 24:11 But the apostles thought that what the women said was nonsense, and they did not believe them. 
42Lk 24:12 But Peter got up and ran to the tomb; he bent down and saw the grave cloths but nothing else. Then he went back home amazed at what had happened. 
42Lk 24:13 On that same day two of Jesus' followers were going to a village named Emmaus, about seven miles from Jerusalem, 
42Lk 24:14 and they were talking to each other about all the things that had happened. 
42Lk 24:15 As they talked and discussed, Jesus himself drew near and walked along with them; 
42Lk 24:16 they saw him, but somehow did not recognize him. 
42Lk 24:17 Jesus said to them, "What are you talking about to each other, as you walk along?" They stood still, with sad faces. 
42Lk 24:18 One of them, named Cleopas, asked him, "Are you the only visitor in Jerusalem who doesn't know the things that have been happening there these last few days?" 
42Lk 24:19 "What things?" he asked. "The things that happened to Jesus of Nazareth," they answered. "This man was a prophet and was considered by God and by all the people to be powerful in everything he said and did. 
42Lk 24:20 Our chief priests and rulers handed him over to be sentenced to death, and he was crucified. 
42Lk 24:21 And we had hoped that he would be the one who was going to set Israel free! Besides all that, this is now the third day since it happened. 
42Lk 24:22 Some of the women of our group surprised us; they went at dawn to the tomb, 
42Lk 24:23 but could not find his body. They came back saying they had seen a vision of angels who told them that he is alive. 
42Lk 24:24 Some of our group went to the tomb and found it exactly as the women had said, but they did not see him." 
42Lk 24:25 Then Jesus said to them, "How foolish you are, how slow you are to believe everything the prophets said! 
42Lk 24:26 Was it not necessary for the Messiah to suffer these things and then to enter his glory?" 
42Lk 24:27 And Jesus explained to them what was said about himself in all the Scriptures, beginning with the books of Moses and the writings of all the prophets. 
42Lk 24:28 As they came near the village to which they were going, Jesus acted as if he were going farther; 
42Lk 24:29 but they held him back, saying, "Stay with us; the day is almost over and it is getting dark." So he went in to stay with them. 
42Lk 24:30 He sat down to eat with them, took the bread, and said the blessing; then he broke the bread and gave it to them. 
42Lk 24:31 Then their eyes were opened and they recognized him, but he disappeared from their sight. 
42Lk 24:32 They said to each other, "Wasn't it like a fire burning in us when he talked to us on the road and explained the Scriptures to us?" 
42Lk 24:33 They got up at once and went back to Jerusalem, where they found the eleven disciples gathered together with the others 
42Lk 24:34 and saying, "The Lord is risen indeed! He has appeared to Simon!" 
42Lk 24:35 The two then explained to them what had happened on the road, and how they had recognized the Lord when he broke the bread. 
42Lk 24:36 While the two were telling them this, suddenly the Lord himself stood among them and said to them, "Peace be with you." 
42Lk 24:37 They were terrified, thinking that they were seeing a ghost. 
42Lk 24:38 But he said to them, "Why are you alarmed? Why are these doubts coming up in your minds? 
42Lk 24:39 Look at my hands and my feet, and see that it is I myself. Feel me, and you will know, for a ghost doesn't have flesh and bones, as you can see I have." 
42Lk 24:40 He said this and showed them his hands and his feet. 
42Lk 24:41 They still could not believe, they were so full of joy and wonder; so he asked them, "Do you have anything here to eat?" 
42Lk 24:42 They gave him a piece of cooked fish, 
42Lk 24:43 which he took and ate in their presence. 
42Lk 24:44 Then he said to them, "These are the very things I told you about while I was still with you�� everything written about me in the Law of Moses, the writings of the prophets, and the Psalms had to come true." 
42Lk 24:45 Then he opened their minds to understand the Scriptures, 
42Lk 24:46 and said to them, "This is what is written�� the Messiah must suffer and must rise from death three days later, 
42Lk 24:47 and in his name the message about repentance and the forgiveness of sins must be preached to all nations, beginning in Jerusalem. 
42Lk 24:48 You are witnesses of these things. 
42Lk 24:49 And I myself will send upon you what my Father has promised. But you must wait in the city until the power from above comes down upon you." 
42Lk 24:50 Then he led them out of the city as far as Bethany, where he raised his hands and blessed them. 
42Lk 24:51 As he was blessing them, he departed from them and was taken up into heaven. 
42Lk 24:52 They worshiped him and went back into Jerusalem, filled with great joy, 
42Lk 24:53 and spent all their time in the Temple giving thanks to God. 
