43Jn 12:16 His disciples did not understand this at the time; but when Jesus had been raised to glory, they remembered that the scripture said this about him and that they had done this for him. 
43Jn 12:17 The people who had been with Jesus when he called Lazarus out of the grave and raised him from death had reported what had happened. 
43Jn 12:18 That was why the crowd met him - -because they heard that he had performed this miracle. 
43Jn 12:19 The Pharisees then said to one another, "You see, we are not succeeding at all! Look, the whole world is following him!" 
43Jn 12:20 Some Greeks were among those who had gone to Jerusalem to worship during the festival. 
43Jn 12:21 They went to Philip (he was from Bethsaida in Galilee) and said, "Sir, we want to see Jesus." 
43Jn 12:22 Philip went and told Andrew, and the two of them went and told Jesus. 
43Jn 12:23 Jesus answered them, "The hour has now come for the Son of Man to receive great glory. 
43Jn 12:24 I am telling you the truth�� a grain of wheat remains no more than a single grain unless it is dropped into the ground and dies. If it does die, then it produces many grains. 
43Jn 12:25 Those who love their own life will lose it; those who hate their own life in this world will keep it for life eternal. 
43Jn 12:26 Whoever wants to serve me must follow me, so that my servant will be with me where I am. And my Father will honor anyone who serves me. 
43Jn 12:27 "Now my heart is troubled - -and what shall I say? Shall I say, 'Father, do not let this hour come upon me'? But that is why I came - -so that I might go through this hour of suffering. 
43Jn 12:28 Father, bring glory to your name!" Then a voice spoke from heaven, "I have brought glory to it, and I will do so again." 
43Jn 12:29 The crowd standing there heard the voice, and some of them said it was thunder, while others said, "An angel spoke to him!" 
43Jn 12:30 But Jesus said to them, "It was not for my sake that this voice spoke, but for yours. 
43Jn 12:31 Now is the time for this world to be judged; now the ruler of this world will be overthrown. 
43Jn 12:32 When I am lifted up from the earth, I will draw everyone to me." 
43Jn 12:33 (In saying this he indicated the kind of death he was going to suffer.) 
43Jn 12:34 The crowd answered, "Our Law tells us that the Messiah will live forever. How, then, can you say that the Son of Man must be lifted up? Who is this Son of Man?" 
43Jn 12:35 Jesus answered, "The light will be among you a little longer. Continue on your way while you have the light, so that the darkness will not come upon you; for the one who walks in the dark does not know where he is going. 
43Jn 12:36 Believe in the light, then, while you have it, so that you will be the people of the light." After Jesus said this, he went off and hid himself from them. 
43Jn 12:37 Even though he had performed all these miracles in their presence, they did not believe in him, 
43Jn 12:38 so that what the prophet Isaiah had said might come true�� "Lord, who believed the message we told? To whom did the Lord reveal his power?" 
43Jn 12:39 And so they were not able to believe, because Isaiah also said, 
43Jn 12:40 "God has blinded their eyes and closed their minds, so that their eyes would not see, and their minds would not understand, and they would not turn to me, says God, for me to heal them." 
43Jn 12:41 Isaiah said this because he saw Jesus' glory and spoke about him. 
43Jn 12:42 Even then, many Jewish authorities believed in Jesus; but because of the Pharisees they did not talk about it openly, so as not to be expelled from the synagogue. 
43Jn 12:43 They loved human approval rather than the approval of God. 
43Jn 12:44 Jesus said in a loud voice, "Whoever believes in me believes not only in me but also in him who sent me. 
43Jn 12:45 Whoever sees me sees also him who sent me. 
43Jn 12:46 I have come into the world as light, so that everyone who believes in me should not remain in the darkness. 
43Jn 12:47 If people hear my message and do not obey it, I will not judge them. I came, not to judge the world, but to save it. 
43Jn 12:48 Those who reject me and do not accept my message have one who will judge them. The words I have spoken will be their judge on the last day! 
43Jn 12:49 This is true, because I have not spoken on my own authority, but the Father who sent me has commanded me what I must say and speak. 
43Jn 12:50 And I know that his command brings eternal life. What I say, then, is what the Father has told me to say." 
43Jn 13:1 It was now the day before the Passover Festival. Jesus knew that the hour had come for him to leave this world and go to the Father. He had always loved those in the world who were his own, and he loved them to the very end. 
43Jn 13:2 Jesus and his disciples were at supper. The Devil had already put into the heart of Judas, the son of Simon Iscariot, the thought of betraying Jesus. 
43Jn 13:3 Jesus knew that the Father had given him complete power; he knew that he had come from God and was going to God. 
43Jn 13:4 So he rose from the table, took off his outer garment, and tied a towel around his waist. 
43Jn 13:5 Then he poured some water into a washbasin and began to wash the disciples' feet and dry them with the towel around his waist. 
43Jn 13:6 He came to Simon Peter, who said to him, "Are you going to wash my feet, Lord?" 
43Jn 13:7 Jesus answered him, "You do not understand now what I am doing, but you will understand later." 
43Jn 13:8 Peter declared, "Never at any time will you wash my feet!" "If I do not wash your feet," Jesus answered, "you will no longer be my disciple." 
43Jn 13:9 Simon Peter answered, "Lord, do not wash only my feet, then! Wash my hands and head, too!" 
43Jn 13:10 Jesus said, "Those who have taken a bath are completely clean and do not have to wash themselves, except for their feet. All of you are clean - -all except one." 
43Jn 13:11 (Jesus already knew who was going to betray him; that is why he said, "All of you, except one, are clean.") 
43Jn 13:12 After Jesus had washed their feet, he put his outer garment back on and returned to his place at the table. "Do you understand what I have just done to you?" he asked. 
43Jn 13:13 "You call me Teacher and Lord, and it is right that you do so, because that is what I am. 
43Jn 13:14 I, your Lord and Teacher, have just washed your feet. You, then, should wash one another's feet. 
43Jn 13:15 I have set an example for you, so that you will do just what I have done for you. 
43Jn 13:16 I am telling you the truth�� no slaves are greater than their master, and no messengers are greater than the one who sent them. 
43Jn 13:17 Now that you know this truth, how happy you will be if you put it into practice! 
43Jn 13:18 "I am not talking about all of you; I know those I have chosen. But the scripture must come true that says, 'The man who shared my food turned against me.' 
43Jn 13:19 I tell you this now before it happens, so that when it does happen, you will believe that 'I Am Who I Am.' 
43Jn 13:20 I am telling you the truth�� whoever receives anyone I send receives me also; and whoever receives me receives him who sent me." 
43Jn 13:21 After Jesus had said this, he was deeply troubled and declared openly, "I am telling you the truth�� one of you is going to betray me." 
43Jn 13:22 The disciples looked at one another, completely puzzled about whom he meant. 
43Jn 13:23 One of the disciples, the one whom Jesus loved, was sitting next to Jesus. 
43Jn 13:24 Simon Peter motioned to him and said, "Ask him whom he is talking about." 
43Jn 13:25 So that disciple moved closer to Jesus' side and asked, "Who is it, Lord?" 
43Jn 13:26 Jesus answered, "I will dip some bread in the sauce and give it to him; he is the man." So he took a piece of bread, dipped it, and gave it to Judas, the son of Simon Iscariot. 
43Jn 13:27 As soon as Judas took the bread, Satan entered into him. Jesus said to him, "Hurry and do what you must!" 
43Jn 13:28 None of the others at the table understood why Jesus said this to him. 
43Jn 13:29 Since Judas was in charge of the money bag, some of the disciples thought that Jesus had told him to go and buy what they needed for the festival, or to give something to the poor. 
43Jn 13:30 Judas accepted the bread and went out at once. It was night. 
43Jn 13:31 After Judas had left, Jesus said, "Now the Son of Man's glory is revealed; now God's glory is revealed through him. 
43Jn 13:32 And if God's glory is revealed through him, then God will reveal the glory of the Son of Man in himself, and he will do so at once. 
43Jn 13:33 My children, I shall not be with you very much longer. You will look for me; but I tell you now what I told the Jewish authorities, 'You cannot go where I am going.' 
43Jn 13:34 And now I give you a new commandment�� love one another. As I have loved you, so you must love one another. 
43Jn 13:35 If you have love for one another, then everyone will know that you are my disciples." 
43Jn 13:36 "Where are you going, Lord?" Simon Peter asked him. "You cannot follow me now where I am going," answered Jesus; "but later you will follow me." 
43Jn 13:37 "Lord, why can't I follow you now?" asked Peter. "I am ready to die for you!" 
43Jn 13:38 Jesus answered, "Are you really ready to die for me? I am telling you the truth�� before the rooster crows you will say three times that you do not know me. 
43Jn 14:1 "Do not be worried and upset," Jesus told them. "Believe in God and believe also in me. 
43Jn 14:2 There are many rooms in my Father's house, and I am going to prepare a place for you. I would not tell you this if it were not so. 
43Jn 14:3 And after I go and prepare a place for you, I will come back and take you to myself, so that you will be where I am. 
43Jn 14:4 You know the way that leads to the place where I am going." 
43Jn 14:5 Thomas said to him, "Lord, we do not know where you are going; so how can we know the way to get there?" 
43Jn 14:6 Jesus answered him, "I am the way, the truth, and the life; no one goes to the Father except by me. 
43Jn 14:7 Now that you have known me," he said to them, "you will know my Father also, and from now on you do know him and you have seen him." 
43Jn 14:8 Philip said to him, "Lord, show us the Father; that is all we need." 
43Jn 14:9 Jesus answered, "For a long time I have been with you all; yet you do not know me, Philip? Whoever has seen me has seen the Father. Why, then, do you say, 'Show us the Father'? 
43Jn 14:10 Do you not believe, Philip, that I am in the Father and the Father is in me? The words that I have spoken to you," Jesus said to his disciples, "do not come from me. The Father, who remains in me, does his own work. 
43Jn 14:11 Believe me when I say that I am in the Father and the Father is in me. If not, believe because of the things I do. 
43Jn 14:12 I am telling you the truth�� those who believe in me will do what I do - -yes, they will do even greater things, because I am going to the Father. 
43Jn 14:13 And I will do whatever you ask for in my name, so that the Father's glory will be shown through the Son. 
43Jn 14:14 If you ask me for anything in my name, I will do it. 
43Jn 14:15 "If you love me, you will obey my commandments. 
43Jn 14:16 I will ask the Father, and he will give you another Helper, who will stay with you forever. 
43Jn 14:17 He is the Spirit, who reveals the truth about God. The world cannot receive him, because it cannot see him or know him. But you know him, because he remains with you and is in you. 
43Jn 14:18 "When I go, you will not be left all alone; I will come back to you. 
43Jn 14:19 In a little while the world will see me no more, but you will see me; and because I live, you also will live. 
43Jn 14:20 When that day comes, you will know that I am in my Father and that you are in me, just as I am in you. 
43Jn 14:21 "Those who accept my commandments and obey them are the ones who love me. My Father will love those who love me; I too will love them and reveal myself to them." 
43Jn 14:22 Judas (not Judas Iscariot) said, "Lord, how can it be that you will reveal yourself to us and not to the world?" 
43Jn 14:23 Jesus answered him, "Those who love me will obey my teaching. My Father will love them, and my Father and I will come to them and live with them. 
43Jn 14:24 Those who do not love me do not obey my teaching. And the teaching you have heard is not mine, but comes from the Father, who sent me. 
43Jn 14:25 "I have told you this while I am still with you. 
43Jn 14:26 The Helper, the Holy Spirit, whom the Father will send in my name, will teach you everything and make you remember all that I have told you. 
43Jn 14:27 "Peace is what I leave with you; it is my own peace that I give you. I do not give it as the world does. Do not be worried and upset; do not be afraid. 
43Jn 14:28 You heard me say to you, 'I am leaving, but I will come back to you.' If you loved me, you would be glad that I am going to the Father; for he is greater than I. 
43Jn 14:29 I have told you this now before it all happens, so that when it does happen, you will believe. 
43Jn 14:30 I cannot talk with you much longer, because the ruler of this world is coming. He has no power over me, 
43Jn 14:31 but the world must know that I love the Father; that is why I do everything as he commands me. "Come, let us go from this place. 
43Jn 15:1 "I am the real vine, and my Father is the gardener. 
43Jn 15:2 He breaks off every branch in me that does not bear fruit, and he prunes every branch that does bear fruit, so that it will be clean and bear more fruit. 
43Jn 15:3 You have been made clean already by the teaching I have given you. 
43Jn 15:4 Remain united to me, and I will remain united to you. A branch cannot bear fruit by itself; it can do so only if it remains in the vine. In the same way you cannot bear fruit unless you remain in me. 
43Jn 15:5 "I am the vine, and you are the branches. Those who remain in me, and I in them, will bear much fruit; for you can do nothing without me. 
43Jn 15:6 Those who do not remain in me are thrown out like a branch and dry up; such branches are gathered up and thrown into the fire, where they are burned. 
43Jn 15:7 If you remain in me and my words remain in you, then you will ask for anything you wish, and you shall have it. 
43Jn 15:8 My Father's glory is shown by your bearing much fruit; and in this way you become my disciples. 
43Jn 15:9 I love you just as the Father loves me; remain in my love. 
43Jn 15:10 If you obey my commands, you will remain in my love, just as I have obeyed my Father's commands and remain in his love. 
43Jn 15:11 "I have told you this so that my joy may be in you and that your joy may be complete. 
43Jn 15:12 My commandment is this�� love one another, just as I love you. 
43Jn 15:13 The greatest love you can have for your friends is to give your life for them. 
43Jn 15:14 And you are my friends if you do what I command you. 
43Jn 15:15 I do not call you servants any longer, because servants do not know what their master is doing. Instead, I call you friends, because I have told you everything I heard from my Father. 
43Jn 15:16 You did not choose me; I chose you and appointed you to go and bear much fruit, the kind of fruit that endures. And so the Father will give you whatever you ask of him in my name. 
43Jn 15:17 This, then, is what I command you�� love one another. 
43Jn 15:18 "If the world hates you, just remember that it has hated me first. 
43Jn 15:19 If you belonged to the world, then the world would love you as its own. But I chose you from this world, and you do not belong to it; that is why the world hates you. 
43Jn 15:20 Remember what I told you�� 'Slaves are not greater than their master.' If people persecuted me, they will persecute you too; if they obeyed my teaching, they will obey yours too. 
43Jn 15:21 But they will do all this to you because you are mine; for they do not know the one who sent me. 
43Jn 15:22 They would not have been guilty of sin if I had not come and spoken to them; as it is, they no longer have any excuse for their sin. 
43Jn 15:23 Whoever hates me hates my Father also. 
43Jn 15:24 They would not have been guilty of sin if I had not done among them the things that no one else ever did; as it is, they have seen what I did, and they hate both me and my Father. 
43Jn 15:25 This, however, was bound to happen so that what is written in their Law may come true�� 'They hated me for no reason at all.' 
43Jn 15:26 "The Helper will come - -the Spirit, who reveals the truth about God and who comes from the Father. I will send him to you from the Father, and he will speak about me. 
43Jn 15:27 And you, too, will speak about me, because you have been with me from the very beginning. 
43Jn 16:1 "I have told you this, so that you will not give up your faith. 
43Jn 16:2 You will be expelled from the synagogues, and the time will come when those who kill you will think that by doing this they are serving God. 
43Jn 16:3 People will do these things to you because they have not known either the Father or me. 
43Jn 16:4 But I have told you this, so that when the time comes for them to do these things, you will remember what I told you. "I did not tell you these things at the beginning, for I was with you. 
43Jn 16:5 But now I am going to him who sent me, yet none of you asks me where I am going. 
43Jn 16:6 And now that I have told you, your hearts are full of sadness. 
43Jn 16:7 But I am telling you the truth�� it is better for you that I go away, because if I do not go, the Helper will not come to you. But if I do go away, then I will send him to you. 
43Jn 16:8 And when he comes, he will prove to the people of the world that they are wrong about sin and about what is right and about God's judgment. 
43Jn 16:9 They are wrong about sin, because they do not believe in me; 
43Jn 16:10 they are wrong about what is right, because I am going to the Father and you will not see me any more; 
43Jn 16:11 and they are wrong about judgment, because the ruler of this world has already been judged. 
43Jn 16:12 "I have much more to tell you, but now it would be too much for you to bear. 
43Jn 16:13 When, however, the Spirit comes, who reveals the truth about God, he will lead you into all the truth. He will not speak on his own authority, but he will speak of what he hears and will tell you of things to come. 
43Jn 16:14 He will give me glory, because he will take what I say and tell it to you. 
43Jn 16:15 All that my Father has is mine; that is why I said that the Spirit will take what I give him and tell it to you. 
43Jn 16:16 "In a little while you will not see me any more, and then a little while later you will see me." 
43Jn 16:17 Some of his disciples asked among themselves, "What does this mean? He tells us that in a little while we will not see him, and then a little while later we will see him; and he also says, 'It is because I am going to the Father.' 
43Jn 16:18 What does this 'a little while' mean? We don't know what he is talking about!" 
43Jn 16:19 Jesus knew that they wanted to question him, so he said to them, "I said, 'In a little while you will not see me, and then a little while later you will see me.' Is this what you are asking about among yourselves? 
43Jn 16:20 I am telling you the truth�� you will cry and weep, but the world will be glad; you will be sad, but your sadness will turn into gladness. 
43Jn 16:21 When a woman is about to give birth, she is sad because her hour of suffering has come; but when the baby is born, she forgets her suffering, because she is happy that a baby has been born into the world. 
43Jn 16:22 That is how it is with you�� now you are sad, but I will see you again, and your hearts will be filled with gladness, the kind of gladness that no one can take away from you. 
43Jn 16:23 "When that day comes, you will not ask me for anything. I am telling you the truth�� the Father will give you whatever you ask of him in my name. 
43Jn 16:24 Until now you have not asked for anything in my name; ask and you will receive, so that your happiness may be complete. 
43Jn 16:25 "I have used figures of speech to tell you these things. But the time will come when I will not use figures of speech, but will speak to you plainly about the Father. 
43Jn 16:26 When that day comes, you will ask him in my name; and I do not say that I will ask him on your behalf, 
43Jn 16:27 for the Father himself loves you. He loves you because you love me and have believed that I came from God. 
43Jn 16:28 I did come from the Father, and I came into the world; and now I am leaving the world and going to the Father." 
43Jn 16:29 Then his disciples said to him, "Now you are speaking plainly, without using figures of speech. 
43Jn 16:30 We know now that you know everything; you do not need to have someone ask you questions. This makes us believe that you came from God." 
43Jn 16:31 Jesus answered them, "Do you believe now? 
43Jn 16:32 The time is coming, and is already here, when all of you will be scattered, each of you to your own home, and I will be left all alone. But I am not really alone, because the Father is with me. 
43Jn 16:33 I have told you this so that you will have peace by being united to me. The world will make you suffer. But be brave! I have defeated the world!" 
43Jn 17:1 After Jesus finished saying this, he looked up to heaven and said, "Father, the hour has come. Give glory to your Son, so that the Son may give glory to you. 
43Jn 17:2 For you gave him authority over all people, so that he might give eternal life to all those you gave him. 
43Jn 17:3 And eternal life means to know you, the only true God, and to know Jesus Christ, whom you sent. 
43Jn 17:4 I have shown your glory on earth; I have finished the work you gave me to do. 
43Jn 17:5 Father! Give me glory in your presence now, the same glory I had with you before the world was made. 
43Jn 17:6 "I have made you known to those you gave me out of the world. They belonged to you, and you gave them to me. They have obeyed your word, 
43Jn 17:7 and now they know that everything you gave me comes from you. 
43Jn 17:8 I gave them the message that you gave me, and they received it; they know that it is true that I came from you, and they believe that you sent me. 
43Jn 17:9 "I pray for them. I do not pray for the world but for those you gave me, for they belong to you. 
43Jn 17:10 All I have is yours, and all you have is mine; and my glory is shown through them. 
43Jn 17:11 And now I am coming to you; I am no longer in the world, but they are in the world. Holy Father! Keep them safe by the power of your name, the name you gave me, so that they may be one just as you and I are one. 
43Jn 17:12 While I was with them, I kept them safe by the power of your name, the name you gave me. I protected them, and not one of them was lost, except the man who was bound to be lost - -so that the scripture might come true. 
43Jn 17:13 And now I am coming to you, and I say these things in the world so that they might have my joy in their hearts in all its fullness. 
43Jn 17:14 I gave them your message, and the world hated them, because they do not belong to the world, just as I do not belong to the world. 
43Jn 17:15 I do not ask you to take them out of the world, but I do ask you to keep them safe from the Evil One. 
43Jn 17:16 Just as I do not belong to the world, they do not belong to the world. 
43Jn 17:17 Dedicate them to yourself by means of the truth; your word is truth. 
43Jn 17:18 I sent them into the world, just as you sent me into the world. 
43Jn 17:19 And for their sake I dedicate myself to you, in order that they, too, may be truly dedicated to you. 
43Jn 17:20 "I pray not only for them, but also for those who believe in me because of their message. 
43Jn 17:21 I pray that they may all be one. Father! May they be in us, just as you are in me and I am in you. May they be one, so that the world will believe that you sent me. 
43Jn 17:22 I gave them the same glory you gave me, so that they may be one, just as you and I are one�� 
43Jn 17:23 I in them and you in me, so that they may be completely one, in order that the world may know that you sent me and that you love them as you love me. 
43Jn 17:24 "Father! You have given them to me, and I want them to be with me where I am, so that they may see my glory, the glory you gave me; for you loved me before the world was made. 
43Jn 17:25 Righteous Father! The world does not know you, but I know you, and these know that you sent me. 
43Jn 17:26 I made you known to them, and I will continue to do so, in order that the love you have for me may be in them, and so that I also may be in them." 
43Jn 18:1 After Jesus had said this prayer, he left with his disciples and went across Kidron Brook. There was a garden in that place, and Jesus and his disciples went in. 
43Jn 18:2 Judas, the traitor, knew where it was, because many times Jesus had met there with his disciples. 
43Jn 18:3 So Judas went to the garden, taking with him a group of Roman soldiers, and some Temple guards sent by the chief priests and the Pharisees; they were armed and carried lanterns and torches. 
43Jn 18:4 Jesus knew everything that was going to happen to him, so he stepped forward and asked them, "Who is it you are looking for?" 
43Jn 18:5 "Jesus of Nazareth," they answered. "I am he," he said. Judas, the traitor, was standing there with them. 
43Jn 18:6 When Jesus said to them, "I am he," they moved back and fell to the ground. 
43Jn 18:7 Again Jesus asked them, "Who is it you are looking for?" "Jesus of Nazareth," they said. 
43Jn 18:8 "I have already told you that I am he," Jesus said. "If, then, you are looking for me, let these others go." 
43Jn 18:9 (He said this so that what he had said might come true�� "Father, I have not lost even one of those you gave me.") 
43Jn 18:10 Simon Peter, who had a sword, drew it and struck the High Priest's slave, cutting off his right ear. The name of the slave was Malchus. 
43Jn 18:11 Jesus said to Peter, "Put your sword back in its place! Do you think that I will not drink the cup of suffering which my Father has given me?" 
43Jn 18:12 Then the Roman soldiers with their commanding officer and the Jewish guards arrested Jesus, tied him up, 
43Jn 18:13 and took him first to Annas. He was the father-in-law of Caiaphas, who was High Priest that year. 
43Jn 18:14 It was Caiaphas who had advised the Jewish authorities that it was better that one man should die for all the people. 
43Jn 18:15 Simon Peter and another disciple followed Jesus. That other disciple was well known to the High Priest, so he went with Jesus into the courtyard of the High Priest's house, 
43Jn 18:16 while Peter stayed outside by the gate. Then the other disciple went back out, spoke to the girl at the gate, and brought Peter inside. 
43Jn 18:17 The girl at the gate said to Peter, "Aren't you also one of the disciples of that man?" "No, I am not," answered Peter. 
43Jn 18:18 It was cold, so the servants and guards had built a charcoal fire and were standing around it, warming themselves. So Peter went over and stood with them, warming himself. 
43Jn 18:19 The High Priest questioned Jesus about his disciples and about his teaching. 
43Jn 18:20 Jesus answered, "I have always spoken publicly to everyone; all my teaching was done in the synagogues and in the Temple, where all the people come together. I have never said anything in secret. 
43Jn 18:21 Why, then, do you question me? Question the people who heard me. Ask them what I told them - -they know what I said." 
43Jn 18:22 When Jesus said this, one of the guards there slapped him and said, "How dare you talk like that to the High Priest!" 
43Jn 18:23 Jesus answered him, "If I have said anything wrong, tell everyone here what it was. But if I am right in what I have said, why do you hit me?" 
43Jn 18:24 Then Annas sent him, still tied up, to Caiaphas the High Priest. 
43Jn 18:25 Peter was still standing there keeping himself warm. So the others said to him, "Aren't you also one of the disciples of that man?" But Peter denied it. "No, I am not," he said. 
43Jn 18:26 One of the High Priest's slaves, a relative of the man whose ear Peter had cut off, spoke up. "Didn't I see you with him in the garden?" he asked. 
43Jn 18:27 Again Peter said "No" - -and at once a rooster crowed. 
43Jn 18:28 Early in the morning Jesus was taken from Caiaphas' house to the governor's palace. The Jewish authorities did not go inside the palace, for they wanted to keep themselves ritually clean, in order to be able to eat the Passover meal. 
43Jn 18:29 So Pilate went outside to them and asked, "What do you accuse this man of ?" 
43Jn 18:30 Their answer was, "We would not have brought him to you if he had not committed a crime." 
43Jn 18:31 Pilate said to them, "Then you yourselves take him and try him according to your own law." They replied, "We are not allowed to put anyone to death." 
43Jn 18:32 (This happened in order to make come true what Jesus had said when he indicated the kind of death he would die.) 
43Jn 18:33 Pilate went back into the palace and called Jesus. "Are you the king of the Jews?" he asked him. 
43Jn 18:34 Jesus answered, "Does this question come from you or have others told you about me?" 
43Jn 18:35 Pilate replied, "Do you think I am a Jew? It was your own people and the chief priests who handed you over to me. What have you done?" 
43Jn 18:36 Jesus said, "My kingdom does not belong to this world; if my kingdom belonged to this world, my followers would fight to keep me from being handed over to the Jewish authorities. No, my kingdom does not belong here!" 
43Jn 18:37 So Pilate asked him, "Are you a king, then?" Jesus answered, "You say that I am a king. I was born and came into the world for this one purpose, to speak about the truth. Whoever belongs to the truth listens to me." 
43Jn 18:38 "And what is truth?" Pilate asked. Then Pilate went back outside to the people and said to them, "I cannot find any reason to condemn him. 
43Jn 18:39 But according to the custom you have, I always set free a prisoner for you during the Passover. Do you want me to set free for you the king of the Jews?" 
43Jn 18:40 They answered him with a shout, "No, not him! We want Barabbas!" (Barabbas was a bandit.) 
43Jn 19:1 Then Pilate took Jesus and had him whipped. 
43Jn 19:2 The soldiers made a crown out of thorny branches and put it on his head; then they put a purple robe on him 
43Jn 19:3 and came to him and said, "Long live the King of the Jews!" And they went up and slapped him. 
43Jn 19:4 Pilate went back out once more and said to the crowd, "Look, I will bring him out here to you to let you see that I cannot find any reason to condemn him." 
43Jn 19:5 So Jesus came out, wearing the crown of thorns and the purple robe. Pilate said to them, "Look! Here is the man!" 
43Jn 19:6 When the chief priests and the Temple guards saw him, they shouted, "Crucify him! Crucify him!" Pilate said to them, "You take him, then, and crucify him. I find no reason to condemn him." 
43Jn 19:7 The crowd answered back, "We have a law that says he ought to die, because he claimed to be the Son of God." 
43Jn 19:8 When Pilate heard this, he was even more afraid. 
43Jn 19:9 He went back into the palace and asked Jesus, "Where do you come from?" But Jesus did not answer. 
43Jn 19:10 Pilate said to him, "You will not speak to me? Remember, I have the authority to set you free and also to have you crucified." 
43Jn 19:11 Jesus answered, "You have authority over me only because it was given to you by God. So the man who handed me over to you is guilty of a worse sin." 
43Jn 19:12 When Pilate heard this, he tried to find a way to set Jesus free. But the crowd shouted back, "If you set him free, that means that you are not the Emperor's friend! Anyone who claims to be a king is a rebel against the Emperor!" 
43Jn 19:13 When Pilate heard these words, he took Jesus outside and sat down on the judge's seat in the place called "The Stone Pavement." (In Hebrew the name is "Gabbatha.") 
43Jn 19:14 It was then almost noon of the day before the Passover. Pilate said to the people, "Here is your king!" 
43Jn 19:15 They shouted back, "Kill him! Kill him! Crucify him!" Pilate asked them, "Do you want me to crucify your king?" The chief priests answered, "The only king we have is the Emperor!" 
43Jn 19:16 Then Pilate handed Jesus over to them to be crucified. So they took charge of Jesus. 
43Jn 19:17 He went out, carrying his cross, and came to "The Place of the Skull," as it is called. (In Hebrew it is called "Golgotha.") 
43Jn 19:18 There they crucified him; and they also crucified two other men, one on each side, with Jesus between them. 
43Jn 19:19 Pilate wrote a notice and had it put on the cross. "Jesus of Nazareth, the King of the Jews," is what he wrote. 
43Jn 19:20 Many people read it, because the place where Jesus was crucified was not far from the city. The notice was written in Hebrew, Latin, and Greek. 
43Jn 19:21 The chief priests said to Pilate, "Do not write 'The King of the Jews,' but rather, 'This man said, I am the King of the Jews.' " 
43Jn 19:22 Pilate answered, "What I have written stays written." 
43Jn 19:23 After the soldiers had crucified Jesus, they took his clothes and divided them into four parts, one part for each soldier. They also took the robe, which was made of one piece of woven cloth without any seams in it. 
43Jn 19:24 The soldiers said to one another, "Let's not tear it; let's throw dice to see who will get it." This happened in order to make the scripture come true�� "They divided my clothes among themselves and gambled for my robe." And this is what the soldiers did. 
43Jn 19:25 Standing close to Jesus' cross were his mother, his mother's sister, Mary the wife of Clopas, and Mary Magdalene. 
43Jn 19:26 Jesus saw his mother and the disciple he loved standing there; so he said to his mother, "He is your son." 
43Jn 19:27 Then he said to the disciple, "She is your mother." From that time the disciple took her to live in his home. 
43Jn 19:28 Jesus knew that by now everything had been completed; and in order to make the scripture come true, he said, "I am thirsty." 
43Jn 19:29 A bowl was there, full of cheap wine; so a sponge was soaked in the wine, put on a stalk of hyssop, and lifted up to his lips. 
43Jn 19:30 Jesus drank the wine and said, "It is finished!" Then he bowed his head and gave up his spirit. 
43Jn 19:31 Then the Jewish authorities asked Pilate to allow them to break the legs of the men who had been crucified, and to take the bodies down from the crosses. They requested this because it was Friday, and they did not want the bodies to stay on the crosses on the Sabbath, since the coming Sabbath was especially holy. 
43Jn 19:32 So the soldiers went and broke the legs of the first man and then of the other man who had been crucified with Jesus. 
43Jn 19:33 But when they came to Jesus, they saw that he was already dead, so they did not break his legs. 
43Jn 19:34 One of the soldiers, however, plunged his spear into Jesus' side, and at once blood and water poured out. 
43Jn 19:35 (The one who saw this happen has spoken of it, so that you also may believe. What he said is true, and he knows that he speaks the truth.) 
43Jn 19:36 This was done to make the scripture come true�� "Not one of his bones will be broken." 
43Jn 19:37 And there is another scripture that says, "People will look at him whom they pierced." 
43Jn 19:38 After this, Joseph, who was from the town of Arimathea, asked Pilate if he could take Jesus' body. (Joseph was a follower of Jesus, but in secret, because he was afraid of the Jewish authorities.) Pilate told him he could have the body, so Joseph went and took it away. 
43Jn 19:39 Nicodemus, who at first had gone to see Jesus at night, went with Joseph, taking with him about one hundred pounds of spices, a mixture of myrrh and aloes. 
43Jn 19:40 The two men took Jesus' body and wrapped it in linen cloths with the spices according to the Jewish custom of preparing a body for burial. 
43Jn 19:41 There was a garden in the place where Jesus had been put to death, and in it there was a new tomb where no one had ever been buried. 
43Jn 19:42 Since it was the day before the Sabbath and because the tomb was close by, they placed Jesus' body there. 
43Jn 20:1 Early on Sunday morning, while it was still dark, Mary Magdalene went to the tomb and saw that the stone had been taken away from the entrance. 
43Jn 20:2 She went running to Simon Peter and the other disciple, whom Jesus loved, and told them, "They have taken the Lord from the tomb, and we don't know where they have put him!" 
43Jn 20:3 Then Peter and the other disciple went to the tomb. 
43Jn 20:4 The two of them were running, but the other disciple ran faster than Peter and reached the tomb first. 
43Jn 20:5 He bent over and saw the linen cloths, but he did not go in. 
43Jn 20:6 Behind him came Simon Peter, and he went straight into the tomb. He saw the linen cloths lying there 
43Jn 20:7 and the cloth which had been around Jesus' head. It was not lying with the linen cloths but was rolled up by itself. 
43Jn 20:8 Then the other disciple, who had reached the tomb first, also went in; he saw and believed. 
43Jn 20:9 (They still did not understand the scripture which said that he must rise from death.) 
43Jn 20:10 Then the disciples went back home. 
43Jn 20:11 Mary stood crying outside the tomb. While she was still crying, she bent over and looked in the tomb 
43Jn 20:12 and saw two angels there dressed in white, sitting where the body of Jesus had been, one at the head and the other at the feet. 
43Jn 20:13 "Woman, why are you crying?" they asked her. She answered, "They have taken my Lord away, and I do not know where they have put him!" 
43Jn 20:14 Then she turned around and saw Jesus standing there; but she did not know that it was Jesus. 
43Jn 20:15 "Woman, why are you crying?" Jesus asked her. "Who is it that you are looking for?" She thought he was the gardener, so she said to him, "If you took him away, sir, tell me where you have put him, and I will go and get him." 
43Jn 20:16 Jesus said to her, "Mary!" She turned toward him and said in Hebrew, "Rabboni!" (This means "Teacher.") 
43Jn 20:17 "Do not hold on to me," Jesus told her, "because I have not yet gone back up to the Father. But go to my brothers and tell them that I am returning to him who is my Father and their Father, my God and their God." 
43Jn 20:18 So Mary Magdalene went and told the disciples that she had seen the Lord and related to them what he had told her. 
43Jn 20:19 It was late that Sunday evening, and the disciples were gathered together behind locked doors, because they were afraid of the Jewish authorities. Then Jesus came and stood among them. "Peace be with you," he said. 
43Jn 20:20 After saying this, he showed them his hands and his side. The disciples were filled with joy at seeing the Lord. 
43Jn 20:21 Jesus said to them again, "Peace be with you. As the Father sent me, so I send you." 
43Jn 20:22 Then he breathed on them and said, "Receive the Holy Spirit. 
43Jn 20:23 If you forgive people's sins, they are forgiven; if you do not forgive them, they are not forgiven." 
43Jn 20:24 One of the twelve disciples, Thomas (called the Twin), was not with them when Jesus came. 
43Jn 20:25 So the other disciples told him, "We have seen the Lord!" Thomas said to them, "Unless I see the scars of the nails in his hands and put my finger on those scars and my hand in his side, I will not believe." 
43Jn 20:26 A week later the disciples were together again indoors, and Thomas was with them. The doors were locked, but Jesus came and stood among them and said, "Peace be with you." 
43Jn 20:27 Then he said to Thomas, "Put your finger here, and look at my hands; then reach out your hand and put it in my side. Stop your doubting, and believe!" 
43Jn 20:28 Thomas answered him, "My Lord and my God!" 
43Jn 20:29 Jesus said to him, "Do you believe because you see me? How happy are those who believe without seeing me!" 
43Jn 20:30 In his disciples' presence Jesus performed many other miracles which are not written down in this book. 
43Jn 20:31 But these have been written in order that you may believe that Jesus is the Messiah, the Son of God, and that through your faith in him you may have life. 
43Jn 21:1 After this, Jesus appeared once more to his disciples at Lake Tiberias. This is how it happened. 
43Jn 21:2 Simon Peter, Thomas (called the Twin), Nathanael (the one from Cana in Galilee), the sons of Zebedee, and two other disciples of Jesus were all together. 
43Jn 21:3 Simon Peter said to the others, "I am going fishing." "We will come with you," they told him. So they went out in a boat, but all that night they did not catch a thing. 
43Jn 21:4 As the sun was rising, Jesus stood at the water's edge, but the disciples did not know that it was Jesus. 
43Jn 21:5 Then he asked them, "Young men, haven't you caught anything?" "Not a thing," they answered. 
43Jn 21:6 He said to them, "Throw your net out on the right side of the boat, and you will catch some." So they threw the net out and could not pull it back in, because they had caught so many fish. 
43Jn 21:7 The disciple whom Jesus loved said to Peter, "It is the Lord!" When Peter heard that it was the Lord, he wrapped his outer garment around him (for he had taken his clothes off ) and jumped into the water. 
43Jn 21:8 The other disciples came to shore in the boat, pulling the net full of fish. They were not very far from land, about a hundred yards away. 
43Jn 21:9 When they stepped ashore, they saw a charcoal fire there with fish on it and some bread. 
43Jn 21:10 Then Jesus said to them, "Bring some of the fish you have just caught." 
43Jn 21:11 Simon Peter went aboard and dragged the net ashore full of big fish, a hundred and fifty-three in all; even though there were so many, still the net did not tear. 
43Jn 21:12 Jesus said to them, "Come and eat." None of the disciples dared ask him, "Who are you?" because they knew it was the Lord. 
43Jn 21:13 So Jesus went over, took the bread, and gave it to them; he did the same with the fish. 
43Jn 21:14 This, then, was the third time Jesus appeared to the disciples after he was raised from death. 
43Jn 21:15 After they had eaten, Jesus said to Simon Peter, "Simon son of John, do you love me more than these others do?" "Yes, Lord," he answered, "you know that I love you." Jesus said to him, "Take care of my lambs." 
43Jn 21:16 A second time Jesus said to him, "Simon son of John, do you love me?" "Yes, Lord," he answered, "you know that I love you." Jesus said to him, "Take care of my sheep." 
43Jn 21:17 A third time Jesus said, "Simon son of John, do you love me?" Peter became sad because Jesus asked him the third time, "Do you love me?" and so he said to him, "Lord, you know everything; you know that I love you!" Jesus said to him, "Take care of my sheep. 
43Jn 21:18 I am telling you the truth�� when you were young, you used to get ready and go anywhere you wanted to; but when you are old, you will stretch out your hands and someone else will tie you up and take you where you don't want to go." 
43Jn 21:19 (In saying this, Jesus was indicating the way in which Peter would die and bring glory to God.) Then Jesus said to him, "Follow me!" 
43Jn 21:20 Peter turned around and saw behind him that other disciple, whom Jesus loved - -the one who had leaned close to Jesus at the meal and had asked, "Lord, who is going to betray you?" 
43Jn 21:21 When Peter saw him, he asked Jesus, "Lord, what about this man?" 
43Jn 21:22 Jesus answered him, "If I want him to live until I come, what is that to you? Follow me!" 
43Jn 21:23 So a report spread among the followers of Jesus that this disciple would not die. But Jesus did not say he would not die; he said, "If I want him to live until I come, what is that to you?" 
43Jn 21:24 He is the disciple who spoke of these things, the one who also wrote them down; and we know that what he said is true. 
43Jn 21:25 Now, there are many other things that Jesus did. If they were all written down one by one, I suppose that the whole world could not hold the books that would be written. 
